      <h1>Earthquake data fundamentals</h1>

      <h4>
        The purpose of this page is to introduce earthquakes, earthquake data fundamentals and where to source earthquake data.
      </h4>

      <br/>

      <p>
        The free dictionary defines earthquake as "A sudden movement of the earth's crust caused by the release of stress accumulated along geologic faults or by volcanic activity" The Free Dictionary (2019).
        Faults are cracks in the crust of the earth that occur between continental plates.
        Earthquakes can be caused by a wide variety of reasons but the most common reason is when there is action within faults. 
        There are three main types of earthquakes caused by this action within faults called Normal Faulting, Strike-slip and Reverse Faulting.
      </p>

      <br/>
    
      <ul>
        <li>
          <img src="./IMAGES/normal.jpg" alt="Normal" style="width: 80px; height: 80px;"> <br/>
          <p style="font-size: x-small;">Dorling Kindersley/Getty Images </p>
          <h5>Normal Faulting</h5>
          <p>Continental plates are moving apart and earth between the plates falls down causing an earthquake</p>
        </li>
        <li><img src="./IMAGES/slip.jpg" alt="Normal" style="width: 80px; height: 80px;"><br/>
          <p style="font-size: x-small;">Mike Dunning/Dorling Kindersle/Getty Images </p> 
          <h5>Strike-Slip</h5>
          <p>Continental plates move away from eachother on a horizontal plane causing earthquakes</p></li>
        <li><img src="./IMAGES/reverse.jpg" alt="Normal" style="width: 80px; height: 80px;"> <br/>
